ted. Fischer-Tropsch formaldehyde synthesis (rxn_015) is plausible on iron-nickel catalysts at hydrothermal conditions but typically yields a range of products with formaldehyde as a minor component. Downstream chemistry is solid.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify iron-nickel alloy or awaruite as catalyst for rxn_015\", \"Note low selectivity for formaldehyde in FT synthesis\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_016\": 0.88, \"rxn_015\": 0.78, \"rxn_004\": 0.85, \"rxn_006\": 0.83, \"rxn_010\": 0.85, \"rxn_011\": 0.88},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.84,\n            \"feedback\": \"Parallel of P5 but through erythrose/thioester route instead of Strecker. Provides useful redundancy. Same Fischer-Tropsch selectivity concern.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Same as P5 suggestions\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_012\": 0.70, \"rxn_013\": 0.85, \"rxn_014\": 0.82, \"rxn_008\": 0.85, \"rxn_009\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.80,\n            \"feedback\": \"Novel pyruvate-based route. The direct reduction of CO2 to pyruvate on magnetite (rxn_012) has some experimental support from Cody et al. and more recent studies, but yields are very low and the reaction is debated. Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde (rxn_013) is well-established. The lactaldehyde intermediate is a creative alternative substrate for Strecker synthesis. Pathway requires formaldehyde from another sub-pathway for rxn_014.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Cite specific experimental evidence for hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis\", \"Consider FeS/NiS mixed catalysts for rxn_012\", \"Note that pathway requires HCHO from hydrothermal sub-network\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_003\": 0.90, \"rxn_017\": 0.88, \"rxn_007\": 0.92, \"rxn_009\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.90,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.92,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.88,\n            \"feedback\": \"The most literature-aligned pathway, directly implementing the Sutherland cyanosulfidic protometabolism. Both homologation steps (HCN\u2192glycolaldehyde and glycolaldehyde\u2192glyceraldehyde) are supported by experimental work from the Sutherland group. The threonine aminonitrile is described in literature as an 'inevitable byproduct' of exactly this chemistry. Environmental progression is Surface\u2192Biochemical (no hydrothermal step), which is acceptable for the cyanosulfidic model that relies on UV surface photochemistry. Missing explicit mention of Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling and UV irradiation.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling as explicit catalyst for rxn_003 and rxn_017\", \"Specify UV irradiation conditions for surface cyanosulfidic reactions\", \"This is the strongest pathway - consider featuring it more prominently\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.90, \"rxn_002\": 0.72, \"rxn_003\": 0.90, \"rxn_005\": 0.88, \"rxn_007\": 0.92, \"rxn_009\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.90,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"Good demonstration of cross-environment convergence: hydrothermal formaldehyde meeting cyanosulfidic glycolaldehyde at the surface for aldol condensation. This is exactly the kind of convergent network topology that makes the overall network robust. The mixing of two independent feedstock streams at the surface is geochemically plausible (vent effluent mixing with surface pool chemistry).\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Elaborate on the geochemical scenario for mixing of hydrothermal and surface chemistries\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_012\": 0.70, \"rxn_013\": 0.85, \"rxn_016\": 0.88, \"rxn_015\": 0.78, \"rxn_014\": 0.82, \"rxn_008\": 0.85, \"rxn_009\": 0.90},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n            \"feedback\": \"Most complex pathway, drawing on two independent hydrothermal channels (pyruvate and Fischer-Tropsch) converging at the surface via aldol condensation. Demonstrates maximum network integration. Accumulates the uncertainties of both rxn_012 and rxn_015, but the redundancy provided by the network means that if either upstream source is weak, alternative pathways compensate.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Acknowledge accumulated uncertainty from two less-established hydrothermal reactions\"]\n        }\