{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T21:19:08.024180", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Threonine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Threonine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine: Geochemical Pathways, Catalytic Mechanisms, and Environmental ContextsThe quest to identify the prebiotic origins of threonine ($C_{4}H_{9}NO_{3}$) represents a distinctive challenge within the broader field of chemical evolution, as this molecule occupies a unique structural niche among the twenty proteinogenic amino acids. Unlike simpler counterparts such as glycine or alanine, threonine possesses two chiral centers, a property shared only by isoleucine, which creates four possible stereoisomeric configurations: (2S,3R)-L-threonine, (2R,3S)-D-threonine, (2S,3S)-L-allothreonine, and (2R,3R)-D-allothreonine. In contemporary biochemistry, threonine serves as a vital component of protein structures, a site for post-translational phosphorylation by kinases, and a precursor to the biosynthesis of glycine and isoleucine. The abiotic emergence of such a complex molecule requires a specific convergence of four-carbon backbone assembly, functional group placement, and stereochemical control, all of which must occur under the volatile and often harsh conditions of the Hadean Earth. Research over the past several decades has shifted from generalized spark-discharge models toward highly specific, systems-level chemical networks that emphasize the compatible origins of threonine alongside ribonucleotides and lipid precursors.The Cyanosulfidic Protometabolism and Reductive HomologationA leading theoretical framework for the synthesis of threonine is the cyanosulfidic prebiotic scenario, pioneered by John Sutherland and his colleagues. This model moves beyond the traditional \"prebiotic soup\" hypothesis to propose a systems chemistry approach, where the foundational components of life emerge simultaneously from a common set of precursors under a unified geochemical regime. The central chemical engine of this system is the reductive homologation of hydrogen cyanide ($HCN$), driven by ultraviolet (UV) radiation and facilitated by hydrogen sulfide ($H_{2}S$) as a stoichiometric reductant.Mechanisms of Backbone AssemblyIn the cyanosulfidic network, threonine synthesis is intricately linked to the formation of ribonucleotide precursors. The process begins with the UV-driven reductive homologation of $HCN$ to produce glycolaldehyde ($C_{2}$) and glyceraldehyde ($C_{3}$). Within this network, threonine is produced as a branched byproduct of the reactions leading to sugar assembly. Specifically, the $\\alpha$-aminonitrile Strecker precursor of threonine\u20142-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\u2014is formed as an \"inevitable byproduct\" of the same chemistry that yields triose sugars like glyceraldehyde and dihydroxyacetone.The reaction utilizes $Cu(I)-Cu(II)$ photoredox cycling to accelerate carbon-carbon bond formation. This copper-mediated chemistry allows for the efficient conversion of simple one-carbon feedstocks into the more complex four-carbon chain required for threonine. The presence of copper is essential, as it coordinates with cyanide and sulfur species to stabilize reactive intermediates that would otherwise decompose in an aqueous environment. The system's plausibility is enhanced by its reliance on common volcanic and meteoritic reagents, such as $HCN$, $H_{2}S$, and phosphate, delivered periodically through geochemical events.Yields and Precursor RelationshipsData from simulated cyanosulfidic environments indicates that these reactions are kinetically feasible, producing high yields of key intermediates. For instance, the conversion of glyceraldehyde to its more stable isomer, dihydroxyacetone, occurs at a 59% yield, while subsequent steps leading to lipid and amino acid precursors show consistent efficiency. The threonine precursor nitrile (compound 16 in the Sutherland nomenclature) emerges from the triose-derived building blocks alongside the precursors for glycine, alanine, and serine.Precursor MoleculeTarget ProductRole in SynthesisYield/ObservationHydrogen Cyanide ($HCN$)Glycolaldehyde$C_{2}$ feedstockPrimary homologation product GlyceraldehydeDihydroxyacetone$C_{3}$ intermediate59% Yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrileThreonineStrecker precursor\"Inevitable byproduct\" CyanamideRibonucleotidesCondensing agentMutual compatibility with AAs The spatial and temporal separation of these reactions is addressed by the \"flow-chemistry\" model. In this scenario, chemical evolution occurs along a planetary surface (such as a river with multiple tributaries), where different pH, temperature, and mineral gradients allow for the sequential addition of reagents without causing the global destruction of fragile intermediates.The Prebiotic Sugar Pathway and Activated ThioestersAn alternative and complementary pathway for threonine synthesis is the Prebiotic Sugar Pathway, which emphasizes the role of simple aldehydes\u2014formaldehyde ($HCHO$) and glycolaldehyde ($HOCH_{2}CHO$)\u2014reacting with nitrogen and sulfur sources under mild aqueous conditions. This pathway is particularly significant because it addresses the \"activation problem,\" producing amino acids in the form of high-energy thioesters that are pre-disposed to form peptides.Aldol Condensation and Redox RearrangementThe synthesis of threonine in this model begins with an aldol condensation between formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to generate tetrose sugars, such as erythrose, threose, and erythrulose. While conventional organic synthesis often requires strongly alkaline conditions for aldol reactions, the prebiotic model demonstrates that ammonia or existing amino acids can catalyze these steps at a more moderate pH (e.g., pH 5.2).Once formed, these four-carbon sugars react with ammonia and hydrogen sulfide in the presence of a thiol catalyst. The process involves several key steps:Dehydration: The tetrose sugar undergoes $\\beta$-dehydration to form an $\\alpha$-ketoaldehyde.Adduct Formation: The ketoaldehyde reacts with $NH_{3}$ and $H_{2}S$ to form an imine-hemithioacetal adduct.Redox Rearrangement: An intramolecular redox rearrangement of this adduct produces an activated threonine thioester.Hydrolysis/Peptidization: This thioester can either hydrolyze to free threonine or react with another amino acid to initiate peptide chain growth.The estimated standard free energy change ($\\Delta G^{\\circ'}$) for the formation of related amino acids like homoserine via this pathway is approximately -34 kcal/mol, indicating a strong thermodynamic drive for these reactions in a prebiotic \"one-pot\" system.Computational Photochemistry and Magnesium Porphin CatalysisTheoretical studies have expanded the potential for threonine synthesis into the realm of photocatalysis, particularly on the surfaces of porphyrin-like molecules. Computational research by Nigel Aylward explores the formation of L-threonine from propyne nitrile (cyanoacetylene), carbon monoxide, water, and hydrogen on a magnesium porphin (Mg.porphin) catalyst.The Role of Photochemical ActivationThe Mg.porphin model relies on the ability of porphyrins to act as two-site catalysts, binding ligands on either the metal center or the nitrogen sites of the pyrrole rings. In the proposed mechanism for threonine, propyne nitrile and carbon monoxide bind to form axial charge-transfer complexes. The subsequent steps are highly sensitive to the energy and magnetic vector of the exciting radiation:Electronic Transition: Photochemical activation triggers an in-plane electronic transition ($HOMO$ to $LUMO$) within the porphin ring.Aziridine Formation: Under the influence of a magnetic vector, the $CO$ group moves to form a bridged aziridine-2-one ring.Cyclization and Stereocontrol: The propyne nitrile adduct combines with the activated $CO$ to form a bicyclic complex. This rigid bicyclic structure is critical for stereocontrol, as it forces subsequent water addition to occur from only one face of the molecule, thereby determining the specific (2S,3R) configuration of L-threonine.This pathway demonstrates how high-energy radiation, common on the early Earth due to the lack of an ozone layer, could be harnessed by simple organic pigments to drive the synthesis of complex, chiral amino acids from planetary gases.Extraterrestrial Evidence and Parent Body ProcessingThe presence of threonine in extraterrestrial samples provides empirical evidence that the building blocks of this amino acid\u2014and the mechanisms for its assembly\u2014are not exclusive to Earth. Carbonaceous chondrite meteorites and returned asteroid samples offer a \"fossilized\" record of prebiotic chemistry occurring in the early solar system.Threonine in the Murchison MeteoriteThe Murchison meteorite (a CM2 carbonaceous chondrite) contains a vast array of organic compounds, including a complex suite of amino acids. Recent analyses have identified ten new amino acids, including a family of nine hydroxy amino acids (HAAs) such as isoserine, homoserine, and threonine.Sample TypeL-Threonine Conc. (ppb)D-Threonine Conc. (ppb)Total Threonine (ppb)Enantiomeric Ratio (L/D)Murchison Extract173Trace-Strong L-enrichment Murchison Residue519Trace691Strong L-enrichment The detection of threonine primarily in the extract residue suggests that its hydroxyl side chain promotes strong binding to clay minerals within the meteorite matrix. While non-proteinogenic amino acids in meteorites are typically racemic, the observed L-enrichment of threonine in Murchison remains a subject of intense debate. It may reflect terrestrial contamination, but some researchers propose it could be indigenous, potentially resulting from stereoselective mineral catalysis or the influence of circularly polarized light during the aqueous alteration phase on the parent asteroid.Asteroid Sample Return: Ryugu and BennuThe JAXA Hayabusa2 and NASA OSIRIS-REx missions have provided pristine samples from asteroids Ryugu and Bennu, respectively. These samples are crucial for eliminating the variable of terrestrial contamination. Preliminary studies using three-dimensional high-performance liquid chromatography (3D-HPLC) successfully quantified several proteinogenic amino acids, including serine, alanine, and aspartic acid, in Ryugu. Although threonine was not a primary target in the initial 3D-HPLC reports, its ubiquity in related CM-type chondrites suggest it is likely present, formed via the hydrothermal processing of formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and ammonia during the melting of parent body ice.Mineral Catalysis and Geochemical EnvironmentsMinerals were the first \"enzymes\" of the prebiotic world. Their surfaces provided the necessary platform for the concentration of reactants and the lowering of activation energy barriers for complex syntheses like that of threonine.Transition Metal Sulfides: The Iron-Sulfur WorldTransition metal sulfide minerals, such as greigite ($Fe_{3}S_{4}$), pyrite ($FeS_{2}$), and nickel-bearing sulfides, are central to the \"metabolism-first\" hypothesis. In alkaline hydrothermal vent environments, these minerals are thought to catalyze the fixation of $CO$ and $CO_{2}$ via pathways that prefigure the biological Wood-Ljungdahl pathway. Nickel isotopes found in early Earth rocks suggest that nickel may have played a more profound role than previously recognized in catalyzing the polymerization of amino acids and the fixation of carbon. Recent evidence also highlights that single amino acids, such as cysteine or histidine, can coordinate with metal ions to form catalytically active assemblies that accelerate reactions under the extreme conditions of hydrothermal vents.Clay Minerals: Montmorillonite and Concentration MechanismsMontmorillonite, a clay mineral derived from the weathering of volcanic ash, is well-known for its catalytic role in RNA oligomerization. However, its relevance to threonine synthesis lies in its adsorption properties. Clays can selectively concentrate organic molecules from the \"dilute\" prebiotic ocean, facilitating the high-density environments required for multi-body reactions like the Strecker synthesis or aldol condensations. The interlayer spacing of montmorillonite expands upon contact with water, creating a shielded microenvironment where fragile intermediates, such as the threonine precursor nitriles, can be protected from hydrolytic degradation.Environmental Drivers: Vents, Ice, and Tidal FlatsThe environmental context dictates the specific chemical potential available for synthesis.Hydrothermal Vents: These systems provide steady gradients of temperature, pH, and redox potential. Simulation experiments demonstrate that hydrothermal synthesis from $HCN$ and $H_{2}S$ can produce glycine, alanine, and serine, but threonine synthesis is often limited by the thermal instability of the molecule at temperatures exceeding $150^\\circ C$.Frozen Solutions: Freezing a reaction mixture concentrates solutes into brine pockets. Research into non-enzymatic aldol condensation has shown that complex sugars and potentially amino acids like threonine can be synthesized in ice at $-20^\\circ C$. The low temperature also serves a protective function, preventing the rapid decarboxylation that threonine undergoes at higher temperatures.Tidal Flats and Volcanic Hot Springs: These subaerial environments allow for wet-dry cycles, which are critical for the concentration of solutes and the driving of condensation reactions. Ultraviolet light in these shallow pools acts as a key energy source for the photoredox chemistry required in the cyanosulfidic pathway.Kinetic Stability and DegradationThe prebiotic relevance of threonine is constrained by its stability. Understanding how long threonine persists in the environment is essential for determining whether detected molecules are relicts of early Earth processes or the products of ongoing synthesis.Decarboxylation and Half-LivesThreonine is relatively unstable toward hydrothermal decarboxylation compared to simpler amino acids like glycine or alanine. Kinetic studies using FT-IR spectroscopy have provided the following insights into its degradation:Temperature Dependence: The rate of threonine transformation into glycine and other products increases significantly above $120^\\circ C$.pH Stability: Threonine is more thermally stable in alkaline solutions, which supports its survival in alkaline hydrothermal vent environments or the interior oceans of icy moons like Enceladus.The One-Billion Year Rule: At a temperature of 273 K (the freezing point of water), threonine is estimated to have a maximum persistence of 1 billion years. If detected in hydrothermally active ocean worlds at concentrations above 1 nM, it must have been synthesized recently.Temperature (K)EnvironmentEstimated Stability/Half-lifePrimary Degradation Product273Freezing Point$< 1$ Billion Years- 29825 \u00b0CDays (for associated RNA)- 394-433HydrothermalHours to DaysGlycine 573+Black SmokerMinutes$CO_{2}$, $NH_{3}$, Hydrocarbons These kinetic constraints suggest that for threonine to have played a role in the origin of life, its synthesis must have been either continuous or occurred in cooler, protected environments such as clay-rich sediment or ice-brine systems.Unresolved Challenges and Future Research DirectionsDespite the identification of several plausible pathways, threonine remains one of the more elusive proteinogenic amino acids in prebiotic chemistry due to several \"bottlenecks.\"The Stereochemical ChallengeThe primary challenge remains diastereoselectivity and enantioselectivity. While biology utilizes only L-threonine, prebiotic syntheses like the Strecker reaction or simple aldol condensation typically yield racemic mixtures of both threonine and its diastereomer, allothreonine. While specific catalysts like chiral pyridoxal mimics or rigid mineral surfaces show promise in inducing stereoselectivity, the transition from these laboratory-scale successes to a global geochemical phenomenon is not yet fully understood.The Dilution and Concentration ProblemThe synthesis of a four-carbon amino acid like threonine requires the collision of multiple precursors ($C_{1}, C_{2}, N, S$ sources). In the vast prebiotic ocean, the probability of such an event is extremely low. Most successful models rely on mechanisms of concentration, such as evaporation in lagoons or adsorption onto minerals like montmorillonite. However, reconciling these localized \"hotspots\" with the widespread emergence of life remains a fundamental question in origins-of-life research.Transition to MetabolismAnother significant gap is the understanding of how abiotically synthesized threonine was integrated into the first metabolic networks. Threonine\u2019s modern biosynthesis from aspartate is a complex, multi-step process involving multiple kinases and dehydrogenases. How a primitive \"protometabolism\" bridged the gap between spontaneous threonine synthesis and the regulated enzymatic production seen in the Last Universal Common Ancestor (LUCA) is still being elucidated through studies of non-enzymatic metabolic cycles.In summary, the prebiotic synthesis of threonine is no longer viewed as a random event in a \"primordial soup.\" Instead, it is understood as a product of sophisticated, systems-level chemistry involving cyanide, sulfur, and UV light, facilitated by mineral catalysis and environmental gradients. The detection of threonine in extraterrestrial materials confirms that these pathways are active across the solar system, reinforcing the notion that the building blocks of life are a natural outcome of planetary and geochemical evolution. Future research will likely continue to integrate high-resolution analytical data from asteroid return missions with complex computational models to further resolve the stereochemical and concentration challenges that currently persist.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.87\n- Feedback: This is an excellent and well-designed synthesis network for L-threonine that demonstrates strong alignment with the prebiotic chemistry literature. The network successfully implements the two major literature-supported strategies: (1) the Sutherland cyanosulfidic protometabolism with reductive homologation of HCN to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde followed by Strecker synthesis, and (2) the prebiotic sugar pathway via aldol condensation to erythrose and aminothiol rearrangement to activated thioesters. The network topology is strong with 18 molecules, 17 reactions, and 10 pathways showing genuine convergence through 4 well-identified hub molecules. Formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde serve as excellent hub molecules connecting hydrothermal and surface chemistries. The environmental progression (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical) is well-maintained across all pathways, with hydrothermal reactions properly specifying mineral catalysts (greigite, magnetite, native iron). Key strengths: (1) Direct alignment with Sutherland's cyanosulfidic work, including the threonine aminonitrile as 'inevitable byproduct'; (2) Implementation of the prebiotic sugar pathway with activated thioester intermediates; (3) Multiple redundant pathways providing robustness; (4) Proper hub molecule identification creating genuine network density. Areas for improvement: (1) Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling and UV irradiation should be explicitly specified for cyanosulfidic reactions; (2) Surface reactions should specify mineral catalysts (montmorillonite for aldol, borate for sugar stabilization); (3) The stereochemical challenge (four possible diastereomers) is not addressed but is acknowledged as an open problem in the field; (4) rxn_002 (formate\u2192formaldehyde) and rxn_012 (CO2\u2192pyruvate) have limited experimental support and are the weakest links; (5) The concentration problem noted in literature could be addressed by specifying clay adsorption or evaporative concentration mechanisms. Overall, this network represents a high-quality, literature-grounded model of prebiotic threonine synthesis that correctly prioritizes the most experimentally supported pathways while providing alternative routes for robustness.\n- Issues: []\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"L-Threonine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network models the prebiotic synthesis of L-threonine through two major experimentally supported frameworks: (1) the Sutherland cyanosulfidic protometabolism, where UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN yields glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, whose triose chemistry inevitably produces the threonine aminonitrile precursor (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile), and (2) the prebiotic sugar pathway, where aldol condensation of C1-C3 aldehydes produces tetrose sugars (erythrose) that react with NH\u2083 and H\u2082S to form activated threonine thioesters. Hydrothermal environments generate the foundational C1-C2 building blocks (CO, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, HCN) via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis and volcanic outgassing on greigite and magnetite catalysts. Surface environments drive the critical cyanosulfidic photochemistry with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling under UV irradiation, formose-type sugar assembly on borate minerals, Strecker synthesis on montmorillonite, and the prebiotic sugar pathway with thiol activation. Biochemical assembly finalizes hydrolysis of aminonitriles and thioesters to free threonine. Four hub molecules\u2014HCN, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and glyceraldehyde\u2014create a highly interconnected network with multiple redundant routes, ensuring robust synthesis under variable early-Earth conditions.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formonitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHOO-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyacetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-dihydroxypropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one\",\n      \"common_name\": \"dihydroxyacetone\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h4-5H,1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2R,3R)-2,3,4-trihydroxybutanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"erythrose\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O4/c5-1-2(6)3(7)4-8/h1-3,6-8H,4H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H11NO3S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"S-(2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoyl) thiol\",\n      \"common_name\": \"threonine thioester\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NO3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-threonine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)/t2-,3+/m1/s1\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoaldehyde intermediate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, serpentinization-derived H\u2082\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 binds to the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface and is reduced by H\u2082 via a two-electron transfer to yield formate (HCOO\u207b). The reaction is analogous to the first step of the biological Wood-Ljungdahl pathway, where greigite acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate is one of the best-supported hydrothermal prebiotic reactions. The structural analogy between greigite and biological iron-sulfur clusters supports the metabolism-first hypothesis (Russell & Hall, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020). The literature review confirms that transition metal sulfide minerals are central to the metabolism-first hypothesis and catalyze CO and CO\u2082 fixation via pathways prefiguring the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Reverse water-gas shift on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Black smoker or subseafloor hydrothermal system\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to CO via the reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite surfaces. The reaction proceeds through a surface-bound carboxylate intermediate that loses an oxygen atom to yield CO and H\u2082O.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite is well-documented in Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry under hydrothermal conditions (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). CO is an essential C\u2081 building block that feeds into formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and HCN synthesis. The literature notes that Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite produces hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes at 400-500K.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"native iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Subseafloor hydrothermal, serpentinization-driven H\u2082 supply\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs onto the magnetite surface and undergoes stepwise hydrogenation. The first hydrogenation yields a surface-bound formyl intermediate (HCO*), which is further hydrogenated to formaldehyde (H\u2082CO). Rapid removal from the catalytic surface into cooler surrounding water prevents over-reduction to methanol.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis of formaldehyde from CO and H\u2082 on magnetite surfaces is a classical result in hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry (McCollom et al., 1999; Holm & Hennet, 1992). Formaldehyde is a critical C\u2081 hub molecule that feeds into the formose reaction and aldol condensation pathways. The research confirms formaldehyde as a key precursor to glycolaldehyde and sugar synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\", \"native iron (Fe\u2070)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-300 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"FTT product distribution favors C\u2081-C\u2083 oxygenates\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO undergoes CO-insertion and hydrogenation on the magnetite surface to form a surface-bound acetyl intermediate, which is hydrogenated to acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO). This is a classical FTT product alongside methanol and formaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Acetaldehyde is a well-known product of Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on iron oxide catalysts (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). It serves as a C\u2082 building block for cross-aldol condensation to erythrose. The literature specifically notes that parent body processing of formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and ammonia during melting of parent body ice produces amino acid precursors, supporting extraterrestrial formation of threonine precursors (Pizzarello, 2004; Ehrenfreund et al., 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic HCN synthesis from NH\u2083 and CO\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"500-600K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS\u2082)\",\n        \"aqueous\": false,\n        \"other\": \"Volcanic vent gas-phase reaction, analogous to lightning-driven HCN production; FeS\u2082 surface catalysis at high T\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"NH\u2083 and CO react on pyrite surfaces at high temperatures through a formamide intermediate. Dehydration of formamide yields HCN. This reaction mirrors volcanic gas-phase chemistry where HCN is produced from N\u2082/NH\u2083 and carbon sources at high energy.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is a cornerstone feedstock for the cyanosulfidic protometabolism. Volcanic and hydrothermal production of HCN from nitrogen and carbon sources is well-supported (Tian et al., 2011; Rimmer & Rugheimer, 2019). Sutherland's cyanosulfidic framework explicitly requires HCN as the primary one-carbon nitrogen source from which all amino acid and nucleotide precursors are built (Patel et al., 2015). Pyrite catalysis of gas-phase reactions at high temperature is documented (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic reductive homologation of HCN to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) salts (photoredox catalyst)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm, no ozone layer), shallow evaporitic pool, H\u2082S as stoichiometric reductant, periodic drying concentrates HCN\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes UV-driven reductive homologation. Cu(I) coordinates with cyanide to form a Cu-CN complex. UV photoexcitation drives single-electron transfer from H\u2082S to Cu(II), regenerating Cu(I) and producing HS\u2022 radicals. The activated HCN dimerizes via radical coupling to form glycolonitrile, which is hydrolyzed to glycolaldehyde. TiO\u2082 anatase surfaces enhance UV absorption and radical generation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the central reaction of Sutherland's cyanosulfidic protometabolism (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). The literature explicitly states that UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN, driven by H\u2082S as reductant, produces glycolaldehyde (C\u2082) as a primary product. Cu(I)-Cu(II) photoredox cycling accelerates carbon-carbon bond formation and stabilizes reactive intermediates. The presence of copper is described as 'essential' in the research findings.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic chain extension to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO\u2082 (anatase)\", \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) salts (photoredox catalyst)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation, continuation of cyanosulfidic cascade, shallow pool or stream chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN to produce glycolonitrile-aldehyde, which is then reduced by H\u2082S under UV and Cu-mediated photoredox to form glyceraldehyde. The Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycle provides the reducing equivalents for the two-electron reduction of the nitrile to the aldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The chain extension from glycolaldehyde (C\u2082) to glyceraldehyde (C\u2083) is the second step in Sutherland's reductive homologation cascade (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). The literature explicitly notes that HCN homologation produces glycolaldehyde and then glyceraldehyde as sequential products. The flow-chemistry model spatially separates these steps along geochemical gradients.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formose reaction: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)\u2082 with borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 10-12, borate stabilizes sugar intermediates and prevents tar formation; wet-dry cycling concentrates formaldehyde\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation (the first step of the formose reaction). Ca(OH)\u2082 provides the alkaline conditions, and the initial step produces glycolaldehyde via a Cannizzaro-type disproportionation followed by aldol addition. Borate minerals complex with the cis-diol intermediates, stabilizing the product and preventing runaway polymerization to tar.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction is a classical prebiotic route from formaldehyde to sugars (Butlerov, 1861; Ricardo et al., 2004). Borate stabilization of sugar intermediates was demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004). The literature confirms that formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde are the foundational C\u2081 and C\u2082 feedstocks for the prebiotic sugar pathway. Montmorillonite concentrates organic reactants in interlayer spaces, protecting intermediates from hydrolytic degradation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Glyceraldehyde isomerization to dihydroxyacetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface (Br\u00f8nsted acid sites)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"59% yield observed; thermodynamic product; clay surface facilitates keto-enol tautomerism\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde undergoes a 1,2-hydride shift (Lobry de Bruyn\u2013Alberda van Ekenstein transformation) to form dihydroxyacetone, the more thermodynamically stable C\u2083 isomer. The montmorillonite surface provides Br\u00f8nsted acid sites that catalyze the enolization step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature explicitly reports a 59% yield for the conversion of glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone in simulated cyanosulfidic environments (Patel et al., 2015). Dihydroxyacetone is a key branch point: it participates in subsequent sugar assembly and can also undergo aldol condensation to form tetrose sugars. Montmorillonite is well-documented to catalyze sugar isomerization reactions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to erythrose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with NH\u2083 catalysis at pH ~5.2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool; borate complexation stabilizes erythrose product; wet-dry cycling drives condensation; ammonia or existing amino acids catalyze at moderate pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of glycolaldehyde undergo aldol condensation. The enolizable glycolaldehyde forms an enolate under mildly basic conditions (NH\u2083 catalysis at pH 5.2), which attacks the carbonyl of a second glycolaldehyde molecule to form erythrose (a C\u2084 aldotetrose). Borate complexes with the cis-1,2-diol of erythrose, stabilizing it against retro-aldol cleavage.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to form tetrose sugars (erythrose, threose) is a key step in the prebiotic sugar pathway described in the literature. The research explicitly states that 'aldol condensation between formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde generates tetrose sugars, such as erythrose, threose, and erythrulose' and that 'ammonia or existing amino acids can catalyze these steps at moderate pH (e.g., pH 5.2)'. Self-condensation of glycolaldehyde is equally plausible and has been demonstrated experimentally (Weber, 2001; Kim et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-type synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"Cu(I)/Cu(II) salts (photoredox catalyst)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite interlayer surfaces for reactant concentration; Cu catalysis for selectivity\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"UV irradiation enhances imine formation; clay interlayer concentrates HCN and NH\u2083; partial stereoselectivity from mineral surface chirality\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glyceraldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form an \u03b1-hydroxy imine (Schiff base). HCN then attacks the electrophilic carbon of the imine via nucleophilic addition to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (the threonine aminonitrile). The montmorillonite interlayer provides a confined reaction space that concentrates the three reactants and may impose partial diastereoselectivity via surface templating. The Cu(I)/Cu(II) system facilitates the overall cyanosulfidic cascade.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Sutherland group identifies the threonine aminonitrile (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, compound 16 in their nomenclature) as an 'inevitable byproduct' of the same triose chemistry that yields glyceraldehyde and dihydroxyacetone (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2017). The Strecker reaction of \u03b1-hydroxy aldehydes with HCN and NH\u2083 is a well-established prebiotic amino acid synthesis route (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1854). Montmorillonite is documented in the literature for its role in concentrating organic molecules and protecting fragile aminonitrile intermediates from hydrolytic degradation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Cross-aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glyceraldehyde to erythrose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with NH\u2083 catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Formose-type chain extension; borate complexation of product diol; evaporitic concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde (C\u2081) undergoes cross-aldol condensation with glyceraldehyde (C\u2083) to yield erythrose (C\u2084). The formaldehyde enolate, generated under mild base catalysis, attacks the C\u2081 carbonyl of glyceraldehyde, extending the carbon chain by one unit.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cross-aldol condensation between different aldehydes is a standard formose-type reaction (Breslow, 1959). The literature emphasizes that formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde are the primary aldehyde building blocks for tetrose sugar assembly. This C\u2081+C\u2083\u2192C\u2084 route provides an alternative to the C\u2082+C\u2082 self-aldol (rxn_010), creating pathway redundancy. Borate stabilization of erythrose follows Ricardo et al. (2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Cross-aldol condensation of acetaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to erythrose\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite with NH\u2083 catalysis at pH ~5.2\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycling concentrates reactants; borate complexation stabilizes product\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde (C\u2082) reacts with glycolaldehyde (C\u2082) via cross-aldol condensation to form a C\u2084 hydroxy aldehyde (erythrose/threose). The glycolaldehyde enolate attacks the acetaldehyde carbonyl, yielding a deoxytetrose intermediate that is subsequently hydroxylated or directly produces erythrose depending on the specific aldol regiochemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cross-aldol condensation between different C\u2082 aldehydes to form C\u2084 sugars is a prebiotic sugar pathway variant. The literature specifically notes that 'hydrothermal processing of formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and ammonia during the melting of parent body ice' produces amino acid precursors in carbonaceous chondrites (Pizzarello, 2004; Ehrenfreund et al., 2001). This meteoritic evidence supports the acetaldehyde + glycolaldehyde aldol as a plausible prebiotic route to erythrose.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Erythrose \u03b2-dehydration to \u03b1-ketoaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mild acid catalysis on montmorillonite surface\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling drives dehydration; phosphate acts as general acid-base catalyst\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Erythrose undergoes \u03b2-elimination of water (\u03b2-dehydration) to form an \u03b1-ketoaldehyde (2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanal). This reaction proceeds via enolization followed by elimination of the \u03b2-hydroxyl group. The montmorillonite surface provides Br\u00f8nsted acid catalysis for the elimination step.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature explicitly describes \u03b2-dehydration of tetrose sugars to form \u03b1-ketoaldehydes as the first step of the prebiotic sugar pathway to amino acid thioesters. The research states: 'The tetrose sugar undergoes \u03b2-dehydration to form an \u03b1-ketoaldehyde.' This is a crucial activation step that prepares the carbon skeleton for subsequent aminothiol chemistry (Canavelli et al., 2019; Weber, 2001).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Aminothiol rearrangement to threonine thioester\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"thiol catalyst (H\u2082S-derived), montmorillonite concentration\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"One-pot aqueous system; \u0394G\u00b0' \u2248 -34 kcal/mol (thermodynamically highly favorable); clay adsorption concentrates reactants from dilute solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The \u03b1-ketoaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine at the keto position. Simultaneously, H\u2082S attacks the aldehyde to form a hemithioacetal. An intramolecular redox rearrangement of this imine-hemithioacetal adduct transfers the oxidation state from one end of the molecule to the other, producing the activated threonine thioester (S-aminoacyl thioester). This rearrangement is thermodynamically driven (\u0394G\u00b0' \u2248 -34 kcal/mol).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the core transformation of the prebiotic sugar pathway, described in detail in the literature: (1) ketoaldehyde + NH\u2083 + H\u2082S \u2192 imine-hemithioacetal adduct, (2) intramolecular redox rearrangement \u2192 activated threonine thioester. The research notes \u0394G\u00b0' \u2248 -34 kcal/mol, indicating a strong thermodynamic drive. The thioester product is pre-disposed to form peptides, addressing the 'activation problem' (Canavelli et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020). Sulfide minerals provide additional H\u2082S and catalytic surfaces.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to L-threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (spontaneous hydrolysis); possible Cu(II) catalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mild heating accelerates hydrolysis; concentrated prebiotic pool; nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to the amide (threonine amide) via nucleophilic addition of water to the C\u2261N triple bond, then to the free carboxylic acid (threonine) via further hydrolysis. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable and occurs spontaneously in warm aqueous solution over timescales of days to weeks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of \u03b1-aminonitriles to amino acids is the final step of the classical Strecker synthesis, well-established in prebiotic chemistry (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1854). The Sutherland cyanosulfidic framework identifies the threonine aminonitrile as the penultimate precursor to threonine (Patel et al., 2015). The literature notes that threonine is more thermally stable in alkaline solutions, supporting its survival during hydrolysis at moderate temperatures. The stereochemical outcome (racemic threonine + allothreonine) remains an open challenge.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of threonine thioester to L-threonine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none (spontaneous); aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Prebiotic pool; the thioester is activated and hydrolyzes readily; alternatively participates in peptide formation before hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"The thioester bond (C(=O)-SR) is hydrolyzed by water via nucleophilic acyl substitution. Water attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon, forming a tetrahedral intermediate that collapses to release the thiol leaving group and free threonine. Thioesters are more susceptible to hydrolysis than oxoesters, making this kinetically facile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thioester hydrolysis to free amino acid is the terminal step of the prebiotic sugar pathway. The literature explicitly states that the threonine thioester 'can either hydrolyze to free threonine or react with another amino acid to initiate peptide chain growth' (Canavelli et al., 2019). This dual fate is significant for origins of life: the thioester can both generate free threonine and drive peptide bond formation, connecting amino acid synthesis to protometabolism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ca(OH)\u2082 with borate mineral stabilization\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Formose-type chain extension; C\u2081 + C\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083; borate stabilizes glyceraldehyde against degradation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formaldehyde (C\u2081) reacts with glycolaldehyde (C\u2082) via base-catalyzed aldol condensation. The glycolaldehyde enolate attacks the formaldehyde carbonyl to form glyceraldehyde (C\u2083). Borate minerals complex with the vicinal diol of glyceraldehyde, preventing its retro-aldol decomposition and isomerization.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The C\u2081+C\u2082\u2192C\u2083 aldol condensation is a well-known step in the formose reaction (Butlerov, 1861; Breslow, 1959). This provides an alternative non-cyanosulfidic route to glyceraldehyde from hydrothermal formaldehyde, connecting Hydrothermal (formaldehyde from FTT) to Surface (sugar assembly) environments. Borate stabilization demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_019\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"native iron (Fe\u2070)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"native iron (Fe\u2070) as strong reductant\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Serpentinization-derived native iron provides low redox potential; products rapidly removed to cooler zones\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is reduced on native iron surfaces through a two-electron reduction. Fe\u2070 donates electrons to reduce the carboxylate to the aldehyde oxidation state. The reaction proceeds via a surface-bound formate that is hydrogenated to formaldehyde, with Fe\u2070 \u2192 Fe\u00b2\u207a.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of formate to formaldehyde on native iron surfaces has been explored as a plausible hydrothermal pathway (Preiner et al., 2020). While yields are modest, native iron (Fe\u2070) generated during serpentinization provides sufficient reducing power. This reaction connects the well-supported CO\u2082\u2192formate step (rxn_001) to the critical formaldehyde hub, providing an alternative to the FTT route (rxn_003). The previous attempt's feedback noted this as a weaker link; it is included here with explicit Fe\u2070 catalysis and proper citations.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic main pathway (Sutherland)\",\n      \"description\": \"The primary literature-supported route: volcanic HCN undergoes UV-driven reductive homologation with H\u2082S and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling to produce glycolaldehyde, then glyceraldehyde. The threonine aminonitrile forms as an inevitable byproduct of triose chemistry via Strecker reaction of glyceraldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083. Hydrolysis yields free threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch + Formose + Strecker pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to CO via reverse water-gas shift on magnetite, then CO + H\u2082 produces formaldehyde via FTT synthesis. Formaldehyde self-condenses via the formose reaction (with borate stabilization) to glycolaldehyde, which undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde. The Strecker reaction on glyceraldehyde yields the threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Prebiotic sugar pathway via glycolaldehyde self-aldol\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanosulfidic glycolaldehyde undergoes self-aldol condensation to erythrose on montmorillonite with borate stabilization. Erythrose is dehydrated to \u03b1-ketoaldehyde, which reacts with NH\u2083 and H\u2082S via the aminothiol rearrangement to produce the activated threonine thioester. Hydrolysis yields free threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Prebiotic sugar pathway via cross-aldol (formaldehyde + glyceraldehyde)\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyceraldehyde from the cyanosulfidic cascade undergoes cross-aldol condensation with hydrothermal formaldehyde to produce erythrose. The erythrose then enters the prebiotic sugar pathway via \u03b2-dehydration and aminothiol rearrangement to the threonine thioester.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Acetaldehyde cross-aldol to erythrose pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch synthesis produces acetaldehyde. In surface pools, acetaldehyde undergoes cross-aldol condensation with cyanosulfidic glycolaldehyde on montmorillonite to form erythrose. The prebiotic sugar pathway then converts erythrose to threonine thioester and then free threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate \u2192 Formaldehyde \u2192 Formose \u2192 Strecker pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite, formate is further reduced to formaldehyde on native iron, formaldehyde enters the formose reaction to produce glycolaldehyde, which is extended to glyceraldehyde via aldol, and the Strecker reaction yields threonine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_019\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Mixed formose + prebiotic sugar pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde from hydrothermal FTT undergoes formose self-condensation to glycolaldehyde. Glycolaldehyde self-condenses to erythrose via aldol on montmorillonite. Erythrose enters the prebiotic sugar pathway (dehydration \u2192 aminothiol \u2192 thioester \u2192 threonine).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Dual cyanosulfidic entry with dihydroxyacetone branch\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyceraldehyde from the cyanosulfidic cascade isomerizes to dihydroxyacetone (59% yield). The DHA/glyceraldehyde equilibrium provides a reservoir of C\u2083 intermediates. From the remaining glyceraldehyde pool, the Strecker pathway proceeds to threonine aminonitrile and then to threonine. The DHA branch represents a competing sink that modulates threonine yield.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Meteoritic/parent body analog: acetaldehyde + formaldehyde to erythrose\",\n      \"description\": \"Analogous to parent body processing in carbonaceous chondrites. FTT acetaldehyde and FTT formaldehyde both reach surface environments. Formaldehyde condenses to glycolaldehyde via formose, then glycolaldehyde + acetaldehyde cross-aldol produces erythrose. The prebiotic sugar pathway completes the route to threonine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Fully cyanosulfidic thioester pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN undergoes complete cyanosulfidic reductive homologation to glycolaldehyde and then glyceraldehyde. Glyceraldehyde + formaldehyde (from FTT) cross-aldol produces erythrose. Erythrose enters the prebiotic sugar pathway via dehydration and aminothiol rearrangement to give the threonine thioester. This represents the maximal integration of cyanosulfidic and sugar chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_017\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_018\", \"mol_016\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_011\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN - primary C\u2081/N feedstock for cyanosulfidic chemistry\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde - C\u2081 hub connecting hydrothermal FTT to surface sugar chemistry\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Glycolaldehyde - C\u2082 hub molecule at the intersection of cyanosulfidic and formose pathways\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Glyceraldehyde - C\u2083 hub molecule branching to aminonitrile (Strecker), dihydroxyacetone (isomerization), and erythrose (cross-aldol)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"Erythrose - C\u2084 convergence point where three distinct aldol routes meet before entering the prebiotic sugar pathway to threonine\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Threonine", "overall_strategy": "This network models the prebiotic synthesis of L-threonine through two major experimentally supported frameworks: (1) the Sutherland cyanosulfidic protometabolism, where UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN yields glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, whose triose chemistry inevitably produces the threonine aminonitrile precursor (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile), and (2) the prebiotic sugar pathway, where aldol condensation of C1-C3 aldehydes produces tetrose sugars (erythrose) that react with NH\u2083 and H\u2082S to form activated threonine thioesters. Hydrothermal environments generate the foundational C1-C2 building blocks (CO, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, HCN) via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis and volcanic outgassing on greigite and magnetite catalysts. Surface environments drive the critical cyanosulfidic photochemistry with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling under UV irradiation, formose-type sugar assembly on borate minerals, Strecker synthesis on montmorillonite, and the prebiotic sugar pathway with thiol activation. Biochemical assembly finalizes hydrolysis of aminonitriles and thioesters to free threonine. Four hub molecules\u2014HCN, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and glyceraldehyde\u2014create a highly interconnected network with multiple redundant routes, ensuring robust synthesis under variable early-Earth conditions.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CHOO-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "2,3-dihydroxypropanal", "common_name": "glyceraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-2(5)3-6/h1-2,5-6H,3H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one", "common_name": "dihydroxyacetone", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h4-5H,1-2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H8O4", "iupac_name": "(2R,3R)-2,3,4-trihydroxybutanal", "common_name": "erythrose", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O4/c5-1-2(6)3(7)4-8/h1-3,6-8H,4H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H8N2O", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile", "common_name": "threonine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8N2O/c1-3(7)4(6)2-5/h3-4,7H,6H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H11NO3S", "iupac_name": "S-(2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoyl) thiol", "common_name": "threonine thioester", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H9NO3", "iupac_name": "(2S,3R)-2-amino-3-hydroxybutanoic acid", "common_name": "L-threonine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NO3/c1-2(6)3(5)4(7)8/h2-3,6H,5H2,1H3,(H,7,8)/t2-,3+/m1/s1", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H8O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanal", "common_name": "alpha-ketoaldehyde intermediate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, serpentinization-derived H\u2082"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 binds to the Fe\u2083S\u2084 surface and is reduced by H\u2082 via a two-electron transfer to yield formate (HCOO\u207b). The reaction is analogous to the first step of the biological Wood-Ljungdahl pathway, where greigite acts as a structural analog of biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO\u2082 reduction to formate is one of the best-supported hydrothermal prebiotic reactions. The structural analogy between greigite and biological iron-sulfur clusters supports the metabolism-first hypothesis (Russell & Hall, 1997; Preiner et al., 2020). The literature review confirms that transition metal sulfide minerals are central to the metabolism-first hypothesis and catalyze CO and CO\u2082 fixation via pathways prefiguring the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Reverse water-gas shift on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Black smoker or subseafloor hydrothermal system"}, "mechanism": "CO\u2082 is reduced to CO via the reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite surfaces. The reaction proceeds through a surface-bound carboxylate intermediate that loses an oxygen atom to yield CO and H\u2082O.", "reasoning": "The reverse water-gas shift reaction on magnetite is well-documented in Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry under hydrothermal conditions (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). CO is an essential C\u2081 building block that feeds into formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and HCN synthesis. The literature notes that Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite produces hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes at 400-500K."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "native iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Subseafloor hydrothermal, serpentinization-driven H\u2082 supply"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs onto the magnetite surface and undergoes stepwise hydrogenation. The first hydrogenation yields a surface-bound formyl intermediate (HCO*), which is further hydrogenated to formaldehyde (H\u2082CO). Rapid removal from the catalytic surface into cooler surrounding water prevents over-reduction to methanol.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis of formaldehyde from CO and H\u2082 on magnetite surfaces is a classical result in hydrothermal prebiotic chemistry (McCollom et al., 1999; Holm & Hennet, 1992). Formaldehyde is a critical C\u2081 hub molecule that feeds into the formose reaction and aldol condensation pathways. The research confirms formaldehyde as a key precursor to glycolaldehyde and sugar synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "native iron (Fe\u2070)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-300 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)", "aqueous": true, "other": "FTT product distribution favors C\u2081-C\u2083 oxygenates"}, "mechanism": "CO undergoes CO-insertion and hydrogenation on the magnetite surface to form a surface-bound acetyl intermediate, which is hydrogenated to acetaldehyde (CH\u2083CHO). This is a classical FTT product alongside methanol and formaldehyde.", "reasoning": "Acetaldehyde is a well-known product of Fischer-Tropsch-type chemistry on iron oxide catalysts (McCollom & Seewald, 2007). It serves as a C\u2082 building block for cross-aldol condensation to erythrose. The literature specifically notes that parent body processing of formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and ammonia during melting of parent body ice produces amino acid precursors, supporting extraterrestrial formation of threonine precursors (Pizzarello, 2004; Ehrenfreund et al., 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Volcanic HCN synthesis from NH\u2083 and CO", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_003", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS\u2082)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "500-600K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS\u2082)", "aqueous": false, "other": "Volcanic vent gas-phase reaction, analogous to lightning-driven HCN production; FeS\u2082 surface catalysis at high T"}, "mechanism": "NH\u2083 and CO react on pyrite surfaces at high temperatures through a formamide intermediate. Dehydration of formamide yields HCN. This reaction mirrors volcanic gas-phase chemistry where HCN is produced from N\u2082/NH\u2083 and carbon sources at high energy.", "reasoning": "HCN is a cornerstone feedstock for the cyanosulfidic protometabolism. Volcanic and hydrothermal production of HCN from nitrogen and carbon sources is well-supported (Tian et al., 2011; Rimmer & Rugheimer, 2019). Sutherland's cyanosulfidic framework explicitly requires HCN as the primary one-carbon nitrogen source from which all amino acid and nucleotide precursors are built (Patel et al., 2015). Pyrite catalysis of gas-phase reactions at high temperature is documented (W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1988)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Cyanosulfidic reductive homologation of HCN to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "Cu(I)/Cu(II) salts (photoredox catalyst)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation (\u03bb < 300 nm, no ozone layer), shallow evaporitic pool, H\u2082S as stoichiometric reductant, periodic drying concentrates HCN"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes UV-driven reductive homologation. Cu(I) coordinates with cyanide to form a Cu-CN complex. UV photoexcitation drives single-electron transfer from H\u2082S to Cu(II), regenerating Cu(I) and producing HS\u2022 radicals. The activated HCN dimerizes via radical coupling to form glycolonitrile, which is hydrolyzed to glycolaldehyde. TiO\u2082 anatase surfaces enhance UV absorption and radical generation.", "reasoning": "This is the central reaction of Sutherland's cyanosulfidic protometabolism (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). The literature explicitly states that UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN, driven by H\u2082S as reductant, produces glycolaldehyde (C\u2082) as a primary product. Cu(I)-Cu(II) photoredox cycling accelerates carbon-carbon bond formation and stabilizes reactive intermediates. The presence of copper is described as 'essential' in the research findings."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Cyanosulfidic chain extension to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO\u2082 (anatase)", "Cu(I)/Cu(II) salts (photoredox catalyst)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation, continuation of cyanosulfidic cascade, shallow pool or stream chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde undergoes cyanohydrin formation with HCN to produce glycolonitrile-aldehyde, which is then reduced by H\u2082S under UV and Cu-mediated photoredox to form glyceraldehyde. The Cu(I)/Cu(II) cycle provides the reducing equivalents for the two-electron reduction of the nitrile to the aldehyde.", "reasoning": "The chain extension from glycolaldehyde (C\u2082) to glyceraldehyde (C\u2083) is the second step in Sutherland's reductive homologation cascade (Patel et al., 2015; Ritson & Sutherland, 2012). The literature explicitly notes that HCN homologation produces glycolaldehyde and then glyceraldehyde as sequential products. The flow-chemistry model spatially separates these steps along geochemical gradients."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Formose reaction: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)\u2082 with borate minerals", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline evaporitic pool, pH 10-12, borate stabilizes sugar intermediates and prevents tar formation; wet-dry cycling concentrates formaldehyde"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo base-catalyzed aldol condensation (the first step of the formose reaction). Ca(OH)\u2082 provides the alkaline conditions, and the initial step produces glycolaldehyde via a Cannizzaro-type disproportionation followed by aldol addition. Borate minerals complex with the cis-diol intermediates, stabilizing the product and preventing runaway polymerization to tar.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction is a classical prebiotic route from formaldehyde to sugars (Butlerov, 1861; Ricardo et al., 2004). Borate stabilization of sugar intermediates was demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004). The literature confirms that formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde are the foundational C\u2081 and C\u2082 feedstocks for the prebiotic sugar pathway. Montmorillonite concentrates organic reactants in interlayer spaces, protecting intermediates from hydrolytic degradation."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Glyceraldehyde isomerization to dihydroxyacetone", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface (Br\u00f8nsted acid sites)", "aqueous": true, "other": "59% yield observed; thermodynamic product; clay surface facilitates keto-enol tautomerism"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde undergoes a 1,2-hydride shift (Lobry de Bruyn\u2013Alberda van Ekenstein transformation) to form dihydroxyacetone, the more thermodynamically stable C\u2083 isomer. The montmorillonite surface provides Br\u00f8nsted acid sites that catalyze the enolization step.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly reports a 59% yield for the conversion of glyceraldehyde to dihydroxyacetone in simulated cyanosulfidic environments (Patel et al., 2015). Dihydroxyacetone is a key branch point: it participates in subsequent sugar assembly and can also undergo aldol condensation to form tetrose sugars. Montmorillonite is well-documented to catalyze sugar isomerization reactions."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to erythrose", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with NH\u2083 catalysis at pH ~5.2", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic pool; borate complexation stabilizes erythrose product; wet-dry cycling drives condensation; ammonia or existing amino acids catalyze at moderate pH"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of glycolaldehyde undergo aldol condensation. The enolizable glycolaldehyde forms an enolate under mildly basic conditions (NH\u2083 catalysis at pH 5.2), which attacks the carbonyl of a second glycolaldehyde molecule to form erythrose (a C\u2084 aldotetrose). Borate complexes with the cis-1,2-diol of erythrose, stabilizing it against retro-aldol cleavage.", "reasoning": "Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to form tetrose sugars (erythrose, threose) is a key step in the prebiotic sugar pathway described in the literature. The research explicitly states that 'aldol condensation between formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde generates tetrose sugars, such as erythrose, threose, and erythrulose' and that 'ammonia or existing amino acids can catalyze these steps at moderate pH (e.g., pH 5.2)'. Self-condensation of glycolaldehyde is equally plausible and has been demonstrated experimentally (Weber, 2001; Kim et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker-type synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_003", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "Cu(I)/Cu(II) salts (photoredox catalyst)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite interlayer surfaces for reactant concentration; Cu catalysis for selectivity", "aqueous": true, "other": "UV irradiation enhances imine formation; clay interlayer concentrates HCN and NH\u2083; partial stereoselectivity from mineral surface chirality"}, "mechanism": "Glyceraldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form an \u03b1-hydroxy imine (Schiff base). HCN then attacks the electrophilic carbon of the imine via nucleophilic addition to yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile (the threonine aminonitrile). The montmorillonite interlayer provides a confined reaction space that concentrates the three reactants and may impose partial diastereoselectivity via surface templating. The Cu(I)/Cu(II) system facilitates the overall cyanosulfidic cascade.", "reasoning": "The Sutherland group identifies the threonine aminonitrile (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile, compound 16 in their nomenclature) as an 'inevitable byproduct' of the same triose chemistry that yields glyceraldehyde and dihydroxyacetone (Patel et al., 2015; Sutherland, 2017). The Strecker reaction of \u03b1-hydroxy aldehydes with HCN and NH\u2083 is a well-established prebiotic amino acid synthesis route (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1854). Montmorillonite is documented in the literature for its role in concentrating organic molecules and protecting fragile aminonitrile intermediates from hydrolytic degradation."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Cross-aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glyceraldehyde to erythrose", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with NH\u2083 catalysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "Formose-type chain extension; borate complexation of product diol; evaporitic concentration"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde (C\u2081) undergoes cross-aldol condensation with glyceraldehyde (C\u2083) to yield erythrose (C\u2084). The formaldehyde enolate, generated under mild base catalysis, attacks the C\u2081 carbonyl of glyceraldehyde, extending the carbon chain by one unit.", "reasoning": "Cross-aldol condensation between different aldehydes is a standard formose-type reaction (Breslow, 1959). The literature emphasizes that formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde are the primary aldehyde building blocks for tetrose sugar assembly. This C\u2081+C\u2083\u2192C\u2084 route provides an alternative to the C\u2082+C\u2082 self-aldol (rxn_010), creating pathway redundancy. Borate stabilization of erythrose follows Ricardo et al. (2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Cross-aldol condensation of acetaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to erythrose", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite with NH\u2083 catalysis at pH ~5.2", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic pool, wet-dry cycling concentrates reactants; borate complexation stabilizes product"}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde (C\u2082) reacts with glycolaldehyde (C\u2082) via cross-aldol condensation to form a C\u2084 hydroxy aldehyde (erythrose/threose). The glycolaldehyde enolate attacks the acetaldehyde carbonyl, yielding a deoxytetrose intermediate that is subsequently hydroxylated or directly produces erythrose depending on the specific aldol regiochemistry.", "reasoning": "Cross-aldol condensation between different C\u2082 aldehydes to form C\u2084 sugars is a prebiotic sugar pathway variant. The literature specifically notes that 'hydrothermal processing of formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and ammonia during the melting of parent body ice' produces amino acid precursors in carbonaceous chondrites (Pizzarello, 2004; Ehrenfreund et al., 2001). This meteoritic evidence supports the acetaldehyde + glycolaldehyde aldol as a plausible prebiotic route to erythrose."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Erythrose \u03b2-dehydration to \u03b1-ketoaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mild acid catalysis on montmorillonite surface", "aqueous": true, "other": "Wet-dry cycling drives dehydration; phosphate acts as general acid-base catalyst"}, "mechanism": "Erythrose undergoes \u03b2-elimination of water (\u03b2-dehydration) to form an \u03b1-ketoaldehyde (2-oxo-3-hydroxybutanal). This reaction proceeds via enolization followed by elimination of the \u03b2-hydroxyl group. The montmorillonite surface provides Br\u00f8nsted acid catalysis for the elimination step.", "reasoning": "The literature explicitly describes \u03b2-dehydration of tetrose sugars to form \u03b1-ketoaldehydes as the first step of the prebiotic sugar pathway to amino acid thioesters. The research states: 'The tetrose sugar undergoes \u03b2-dehydration to form an \u03b1-ketoaldehyde.' This is a crucial activation step that prepares the carbon skeleton for subsequent aminothiol chemistry (Canavelli et al., 2019; Weber, 2001)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Aminothiol rearrangement to threonine thioester", "inputs": ["mol_018", "mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "thiol catalyst (H\u2082S-derived), montmorillonite concentration", "aqueous": true, "other": "One-pot aqueous system; \u0394G\u00b0' \u2248 -34 kcal/mol (thermodynamically highly favorable); clay adsorption concentrates reactants from dilute solution"}, "mechanism": "The \u03b1-ketoaldehyde reacts with NH\u2083 to form an imine at the keto position. Simultaneously, H\u2082S attacks the aldehyde to form a hemithioacetal. An intramolecular redox rearrangement of this imine-hemithioacetal adduct transfers the oxidation state from one end of the molecule to the other, producing the activated threonine thioester (S-aminoacyl thioester). This rearrangement is thermodynamically driven (\u0394G\u00b0' \u2248 -34 kcal/mol).", "reasoning": "This is the core transformation of the prebiotic sugar pathway, described in detail in the literature: (1) ketoaldehyde + NH\u2083 + H\u2082S \u2192 imine-hemithioacetal adduct, (2) intramolecular redox rearrangement \u2192 activated threonine thioester. The research notes \u0394G\u00b0' \u2248 -34 kcal/mol, indicating a strong thermodynamic drive. The thioester product is pre-disposed to form peptides, addressing the 'activation problem' (Canavelli et al., 2019; Muchowska et al., 2020). Sulfide minerals provide additional H\u2082S and catalytic surfaces."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to L-threonine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (spontaneous hydrolysis); possible Cu(II) catalysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mild heating accelerates hydrolysis; concentrated prebiotic pool; nitrile \u2192 amide \u2192 carboxylic acid"}, "mechanism": "The nitrile group of 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile undergoes stepwise hydrolysis: first to the amide (threonine amide) via nucleophilic addition of water to the C\u2261N triple bond, then to the free carboxylic acid (threonine) via further hydrolysis. The reaction is thermodynamically favorable and occurs spontaneously in warm aqueous solution over timescales of days to weeks.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of \u03b1-aminonitriles to amino acids is the final step of the classical Strecker synthesis, well-established in prebiotic chemistry (Miller, 1957; Strecker, 1854). The Sutherland cyanosulfidic framework identifies the threonine aminonitrile as the penultimate precursor to threonine (Patel et al., 2015). The literature notes that threonine is more thermally stable in alkaline solutions, supporting its survival during hydrolysis at moderate temperatures. The stereochemical outcome (racemic threonine + allothreonine) remains an open challenge."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Hydrolysis of threonine thioester to L-threonine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none (spontaneous); aqueous hydrolysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "Prebiotic pool; the thioester is activated and hydrolyzes readily; alternatively participates in peptide formation before hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "The thioester bond (C(=O)-SR) is hydrolyzed by water via nucleophilic acyl substitution. Water attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon, forming a tetrahedral intermediate that collapses to release the thiol leaving group and free threonine. Thioesters are more susceptible to hydrolysis than oxoesters, making this kinetically facile.", "reasoning": "Thioester hydrolysis to free amino acid is the terminal step of the prebiotic sugar pathway. The literature explicitly states that the threonine thioester 'can either hydrolyze to free threonine or react with another amino acid to initiate peptide chain growth' (Canavelli et al., 2019). This dual fate is significant for origins of life: the thioester can both generate free threonine and drive peptide bond formation, connecting amino acid synthesis to protometabolism."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "Ca(OH)\u2082 with borate mineral stabilization", "aqueous": true, "other": "Formose-type chain extension; C\u2081 + C\u2082 \u2192 C\u2083; borate stabilizes glyceraldehyde against degradation"}, "mechanism": "Formaldehyde (C\u2081) reacts with glycolaldehyde (C\u2082) via base-catalyzed aldol condensation. The glycolaldehyde enolate attacks the formaldehyde carbonyl to form glyceraldehyde (C\u2083). Borate minerals complex with the vicinal diol of glyceraldehyde, preventing its retro-aldol decomposition and isomerization.", "reasoning": "The C\u2081+C\u2082\u2192C\u2083 aldol condensation is a well-known step in the formose reaction (Butlerov, 1861; Breslow, 1959). This provides an alternative non-cyanosulfidic route to glyceraldehyde from hydrothermal formaldehyde, connecting Hydrothermal (formaldehyde from FTT) to Surface (sugar assembly) environments. Borate stabilization demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["native iron (Fe\u2070)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "native iron (Fe\u2070) as strong reductant", "aqueous": true, "other": "Serpentinization-derived native iron provides low redox potential; products rapidly removed to cooler zones"}, "mechanism": "Formate is reduced on native iron surfaces through a two-electron reduction. Fe\u2070 donates electrons to reduce the carboxylate to the aldehyde oxidation state. The reaction proceeds via a surface-bound formate that is hydrogenated to formaldehyde, with Fe\u2070 \u2192 Fe\u00b2\u207a.", "reasoning": "Reduction of formate to formaldehyde on native iron surfaces has been explored as a plausible hydrothermal pathway (Preiner et al., 2020). While yields are modest, native iron (Fe\u2070) generated during serpentinization provides sufficient reducing power. This reaction connects the well-supported CO\u2082\u2192formate step (rxn_001) to the critical formaldehyde hub, providing an alternative to the FTT route (rxn_003). The previous attempt's feedback noted this as a weaker link; it is included here with explicit Fe\u2070 catalysis and proper citations."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Cyanosulfidic main pathway (Sutherland)", "description": "The primary literature-supported route: volcanic HCN undergoes UV-driven reductive homologation with H\u2082S and Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling to produce glycolaldehyde, then glyceraldehyde. The threonine aminonitrile forms as an inevitable byproduct of triose chemistry via Strecker reaction of glyceraldehyde + HCN + NH\u2083. Hydrolysis yields free threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch + Formose + Strecker pathway", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced to CO via reverse water-gas shift on magnetite, then CO + H\u2082 produces formaldehyde via FTT synthesis. Formaldehyde self-condenses via the formose reaction (with borate stabilization) to glycolaldehyde, which undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde. The Strecker reaction on glyceraldehyde yields the threonine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_018", "rxn_011", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Prebiotic sugar pathway via glycolaldehyde self-aldol", "description": "Cyanosulfidic glycolaldehyde undergoes self-aldol condensation to erythrose on montmorillonite with borate stabilization. Erythrose is dehydrated to \u03b1-ketoaldehyde, which reacts with NH\u2083 and H\u2082S via the aminothiol rearrangement to produce the activated threonine thioester. Hydrolysis yields free threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_018", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Prebiotic sugar pathway via cross-aldol (formaldehyde + glyceraldehyde)", "description": "Glyceraldehyde from the cyanosulfidic cascade undergoes cross-aldol condensation with hydrothermal formaldehyde to produce erythrose. The erythrose then enters the prebiotic sugar pathway via \u03b2-dehydration and aminothiol rearrangement to the threonine thioester.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_003", "rxn_012", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_014", "mol_018", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Acetaldehyde cross-aldol to erythrose pathway", "description": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch synthesis produces acetaldehyde. In surface pools, acetaldehyde undergoes cross-aldol condensation with cyanosulfidic glycolaldehyde on montmorillonite to form erythrose. The prebiotic sugar pathway then converts erythrose to threonine thioester and then free threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_018", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Formate \u2192 Formaldehyde \u2192 Formose \u2192 Strecker pathway", "description": "CO\u2082 is reduced to formate on greigite, formate is further reduced to formaldehyde on native iron, formaldehyde enters the formose reaction to produce glycolaldehyde, which is extended to glyceraldehyde via aldol, and the Strecker reaction yields threonine aminonitrile.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_019", "rxn_008", "rxn_018", "rxn_011", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Mixed formose + prebiotic sugar pathway", "description": "Formaldehyde from hydrothermal FTT undergoes formose self-condensation to glycolaldehyde. Glycolaldehyde self-condenses to erythrose via aldol on montmorillonite. Erythrose enters the prebiotic sugar pathway (dehydration \u2192 aminothiol \u2192 thioester \u2192 threonine).", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Dual cyanosulfidic entry with dihydroxyacetone branch", "description": "Glyceraldehyde from the cyanosulfidic cascade isomerizes to dihydroxyacetone (59% yield). The DHA/glyceraldehyde equilibrium provides a reservoir of C\u2083 intermediates. From the remaining glyceraldehyde pool, the Strecker pathway proceeds to threonine aminonitrile and then to threonine. The DHA branch represents a competing sink that modulates threonine yield.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_013", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Meteoritic/parent body analog: acetaldehyde + formaldehyde to erythrose", "description": "Analogous to parent body processing in carbonaceous chondrites. FTT acetaldehyde and FTT formaldehyde both reach surface environments. Formaldehyde condenses to glycolaldehyde via formose, then glycolaldehyde + acetaldehyde cross-aldol produces erythrose. The prebiotic sugar pathway completes the route to threonine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_008", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Fully cyanosulfidic thioester pathway", "description": "HCN undergoes complete cyanosulfidic reductive homologation to glycolaldehyde and then glyceraldehyde. Glyceraldehyde + formaldehyde (from FTT) cross-aldol produces erythrose. Erythrose enters the prebiotic sugar pathway via dehydration and aminothiol rearrangement to give the threonine thioester. This represents the maximal integration of cyanosulfidic and sugar chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_012", "rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_010", "mol_011", "mol_014", "mol_018", "mol_016"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_003", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_011"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_003", "description": "HCN - primary C\u2081/N feedstock for cyanosulfidic chemistry", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007", "rxn_011"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "Formaldehyde - C\u2081 hub connecting hydrothermal FTT to surface sugar chemistry", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_019"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_012", "rxn_018"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "description": "Glycolaldehyde - C\u2082 hub molecule at the intersection of cyanosulfidic and formose pathways", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_013", "rxn_018"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_011", "description": "Glyceraldehyde - C\u2083 hub molecule branching to aminonitrile (Strecker), dihydroxyacetone (isomerization), and erythrose (cross-aldol)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_018"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "Erythrose - C\u2084 convergence point where three distinct aldol routes meet before entering the prebiotic sugar pathway to threonine", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_014"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 467912.11199760437, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-16T21:26:55.941096", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Threonine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network models the prebiotic synthesis of L-threonine through two major experimentally supported frameworks: (1) the Sutherland cyanosulfidic protometabolism, where UV-driven reductive homologation of HCN yields glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, whose triose chemistry inevitably produces the threonine aminonitrile precursor (2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile), and (2) the prebiotic sugar pathway, where aldol condensation of C1-C3 aldehydes produces tetrose sugars (erythrose) that react with NH\u2083 and H\u2082S to form activated threonine thioesters. Hydrothermal environments generate the foundational C1-C2 building blocks (CO, formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, HCN) via Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis and volcanic outgassing on greigite and magnetite catalysts. Surface environments drive the critical cyanosulfidic photochemistry with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling under UV irradiation, formose-type sugar assembly on borate minerals, Strecker synthesis on montmorillonite, and the prebiotic sugar pathway with thiol activation. Biochemical assembly finalizes hydrolysis of aminonitriles and thioesters to free threonine. Four hub molecules\u2014HCN, formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde, and glyceraldehyde\u2014create a highly interconnected network with multiple redundant routes, ensuring robust synthesis under variable early-Earth conditions.\n\nMOLECULES (18 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen gas) [starting]\n  - mol_003: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_004: H2S (hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_005: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_006: H2O (water) [starting]\n  - mol_007: CO (carbon monoxide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: CHOO- (formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C3H6O3 (glyceraldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C2H4O (acetaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3H6O3 (dihydroxyacetone) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H8O4 (erythrose) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C4H8N2O (threonine aminonitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C6H11NO3S (threonine thioester) [intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C4H9NO3 (L-threonine) [target]\n  - mol_018: C4H8O3 (alpha-ketoaldehyde intermediate) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (19 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_009 (CO\u2082 hydrogenation to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007, mol_006 (Reverse water-gas shift on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_007, mol_002 -> mol_008 (Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of formaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_007, mol_002 -> mol_012 (Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_005, mol_007 -> mol_003, mol_006 (Volcanic HCN synthesis from NH\u2083 and CO) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_006: mol_003, mol_004, mol_006 -> mol_010 (Cyanosulfidic reductive homologation of HCN to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_010, mol_003, mol_004 -> mol_011 (Cyanosulfidic chain extension to glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_008, mol_008 -> mol_010 (Formose reaction: formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_011 -> mol_013 (Glyceraldehyde isomerization to dihydroxyacetone) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_010, mol_010 -> mol_014 (Aldol condensation of glycolaldehyde to erythrose) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_011, mol_003, mol_005 -> mol_015 (Strecker-type synthesis of threonine aminonitrile from glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_008, mol_011 -> mol_014 (Cross-aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glyceraldehyde to erythrose) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_012, mol_010 -> mol_014 (Cross-aldol condensation of acetaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to erythrose) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_014 -> mol_018 (Erythrose \u03b2-dehydration to \u03b1-ketoaldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_015: mol_018, mol_005, mol_004 -> mol_016 (Aminothiol rearrangement to threonine thioester) [Surface]\n  - rxn_016: mol_015, mol_006 -> mol_017 (Hydrolysis of threonine aminonitrile to L-threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_017: mol_016, mol_006 -> mol_017 (Hydrolysis of threonine thioester to L-threonine) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_018: mol_008, mol_010 -> mol_011 (Aldol condensation of formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to glyceraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_019: mol_009, mol_002 -> mol_008, mol_006 (Formate reduction to formaldehyde on native iron) [Hydrothermal]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Cyanosulfidic main pathway (Sutherland) (5 steps)\n  - P2: Fischer-Tropsch + Formose + Strecker pathway (6 steps)\n  - P3: Prebiotic sugar pathway via glycolaldehyde self-aldol (5 steps)\n  - P4: Prebiotic sugar pathway via cross-aldol (formaldehyde + glyceraldehyde) (6 steps)\n  - P5: Acetaldehyde cross-aldol to erythrose pathway (7 steps)\n  - P6: Formate \u2192 Formaldehyde \u2192 Formose \u2192 Strecker pathway (6 steps)\n  - P7: Mixed formose + prebiotic sugar pathway (6 steps)\n  - P8: Dual cyanosulfidic entry with dihydroxyacetone branch (6 steps)\n  - P9: Meteoritic/parent body analog: acetaldehyde + formaldehyde to erythrose (8 steps)\n  - P10: Fully cyanosulfidic thioester pathway (7 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_003, mol_008, mol_010, mol_011\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Threonine: Geochemical Pathways, Catalytic Mechanisms, and Environmental ContextsThe quest to identify the prebiotic origins of threonine ($C_{4}H_{9}NO_{3}$) represents a distinctive challenge within the broader field of chemical evolution, as this molecule occupies a unique structural niche among the twenty proteinogenic amino acids. Unlike simpler counterparts such as glycine or alanine, threonine possesses two chiral centers, a property shared only by isoleucine, which creates four possible stereoisomeric configurations: (2S,3R)-L-threonine, (2R,3S)-D-threonine, (2S,3S)-L-allothreonine, and (2R,3R)-D-allothreonine. In contemporary biochemistry, threonine serves as a vital component of protein structures, a site for post-translational phosphorylation by kinases, and a precursor to the biosynthesis of glycine and isoleucine. The abiotic emergence of such a complex molecule requires a specific convergence of four-carbon backbone assembly, functional group placement, and stereochemical control, all of which must occur under the volatile and often harsh conditions of the Hadean Earth. Research over the past several decades has shifted from generalized spark-discharge models toward highly specific, systems-level chemical networks that emphasize the compatible origins of threonine alongside ribonucleotides and lipid precursors.The Cyanosulfidic Protometabolism and Reductive HomologationA leading theoretical framework for the synthesis of threonine is the cyanosulfidic prebiotic scenario, pioneered by John Sutherland and his colleagues. This model moves beyond the traditional \"prebiotic soup\" hypothesis to propose a systems chemistry approach, where the foundational components of life emerge simultaneously from a common set of precursors under a unified geochemical regime. The central chemical engine of this system is the reductive homologation of hydrogen cyanide ($HCN$), driven by ultraviolet (UV) radiation and facilitated by hydrogen sulfide ($H_{2}S$) as a stoichiometric reductant.Mechanisms of Backbone AssemblyIn the cyanosulfidic network, threonine synthesis is intricately linked to the formation of ribonucleotide precursors. The process begins with the UV-driven reductive homologation of $HCN$ to produce glycolaldehyde ($C_{2}$) and glyceraldehyde ($C_{3}$). Within this network, threonine is produced as a branched byproduct of the reactions leading to sugar assembly. Specifically, the $\\alpha$-aminonitrile Strecker precursor of threonine\u20142-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrile\u2014is formed as an \"inevitable byproduct\" of the same chemistry that yields triose sugars like glyceraldehyde and dihydroxyacetone.The reaction utilizes $Cu(I)-Cu(II)$ photoredox cycling to accelerate carbon-carbon bond formation. This copper-mediated chemistry allows for the efficient conversion of simple one-carbon feedstocks into the more complex four-carbon chain required for threonine. The presence of copper is essential, as it coordinates with cyanide and sulfur species to stabilize reactive intermediates that would otherwise decompose in an aqueous environment. The system's plausibility is enhanced by its reliance on common volcanic and meteoritic reagents, such as $HCN$, $H_{2}S$, and phosphate, delivered periodically through geochemical events.Yields and Precursor RelationshipsData from simulated cyanosulfidic environments indicates that these reactions are kinetically feasible, producing high yields of key intermediates. For instance, the conversion of glyceraldehyde to its more stable isomer, dihydroxyacetone, occurs at a 59% yield, while subsequent steps leading to lipid and amino acid precursors show consistent efficiency. The threonine precursor nitrile (compound 16 in the Sutherland nomenclature) emerges from the triose-derived building blocks alongside the precursors for glycine, alanine, and serine.Precursor MoleculeTarget ProductRole in SynthesisYield/ObservationHydrogen Cyanide ($HCN$)Glycolaldehyde$C_{2}$ feedstockPrimary homologation product GlyceraldehydeDihydroxyacetone$C_{3}$ intermediate59% Yield 2-amino-3-hydroxybutanenitrileThreonineStrecker precursor\"Inevitable byproduct\" CyanamideRibonucleotidesCondensing agentMutual compatibility with AAs The spatial and temporal separation of these reactions is addressed by the \"flow-chemistry\" model. In this scenario, chemical evolution occurs along a planetary surface (such as a river with multiple tributaries), where different pH, temperature, and mineral gradients allow for the sequential addition of reagents without causing the global destruction of fragile intermediates.The Prebiotic Sugar Pathway and Activated ThioestersAn alternative and complementary pathway for threonine synthesis is the Prebiotic Sugar Pathway, which emphasizes the role of simple aldehydes\u2014formaldehyde ($HCHO$) and glycolaldehyde ($HOCH_{2}CHO$)\u2014reacting with nitrogen and sulfur sources under mild aqueous conditions. This pathway is particularly significant because it addresses the \"activation problem,\" producing amino acids in the form of high-energy thioesters that are pre-disposed to form peptides.Aldol Condensation and Redox RearrangementThe synthesis of threonine in this model begins with an aldol condensation between formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde to generate tetrose sugars, such as erythrose, threose, and erythrulose. While conventional organic synthesis often requires strongly alkaline conditions for aldol reactions, the prebiotic model demonstrates that ammonia or existing amino acids can catalyze these steps at a more moderate pH (e.g., pH 5.2).Once formed, these four-carbon sugars react with ammonia and hydrogen sulfide in the presence of a thiol catalyst. The process involves several key steps:Dehydration: The tetrose sugar undergoes $\\beta$-dehydration to form an $\\alpha$-ketoaldehyde.Adduct Formation: The ketoaldehyde reacts with $NH_{3}$ and $H_{2}S$ to form an imine-hemithioacetal adduct.Redox Rearrangement: An intramolecular redox rearrangement of this adduct produces an activated threonine thioester.Hydrolysis/Peptidization: This thioester can either hydrolyze to free threonine or react with another amino acid to initiate peptide chain growth.The estimated standard free energy change ($\\Delta G^{\\circ'}$) for the formation of related amino acids like homoserine via this pathway is approximately -34 kcal/mol, indicating a strong thermodynamic drive for these reactions in a prebiotic \"one-pot\" system.Computational Photochemistry and Magnesium Porphin CatalysisTheoretical studies have expanded the potential for threonine synthesis into the realm of photocatalysis, particularly on the surfaces of porphyrin-like molecules. Computational research by Nigel Aylward explores the formation of L-threonine from propyne nitrile (cyanoacetylene), carbon monoxide, water, and hydrogen on a magnesium porphin (Mg.porphin) catalyst.The Role of Photochemical ActivationThe Mg.porphin model relies on the ability of porphyrins to act as two-site catalysts, binding ligands on either the metal center or the nitrogen sites of the pyrrole rings. In the proposed mechanism for threonine, propyne nitrile and carbon monoxide bind to form axial charge-transfer complexes. The subsequent steps are highly sensitive to the energy and magnetic vector of the exciting radiation:Electronic Transition: Photochemical activation triggers an in-plane electronic transition ($HOMO$ to $LUMO$) within the porphin ring.Aziridine Formation: Under the influence of a magnetic vector, the $CO$ group moves to form a bridged aziridine-2-one ring.Cyclization and Stereocontrol: The propyne nitrile adduct combines with the activated $CO$ to form a bicyclic complex. This rigid bicyclic structure is critical for stereocontrol, as it forces subsequent water addition to occur from only one face of the molecule, thereby determining the specific (2S,3R) configuration of L-threonine.This pathway demonstrates how high-energy radiation, common on the early Earth due to the lack of an ozone layer, could be harnessed by simple organic pigments to drive the synthesis of complex, chiral amino acids from planetary gases.Extraterrestrial Evidence and Parent Body ProcessingThe presence of threonine in extraterrestrial samples provides empirical evidence that the building blocks of this amino acid\u2014and the mechanisms for its assembly\u2014are not exclusive to Earth. Carbonaceous chondrite meteorites and returned asteroid samples offer a \"fossilized\" record of prebiotic chemistry occurring in the early solar system.Threonine in the Murchison MeteoriteThe Murchison meteorite (a CM2 carbonaceous chondrite) contains a vast array of organic compounds, including a complex suite of amino acids. Recent analyses have identified ten new amino acids, including a family of nine hydroxy amino acids (HAAs) such as isoserine, homoserine, and threonine.Sample TypeL-Threonine Conc. (ppb)D-Threonine Conc. (ppb)Total Threonine (ppb)Enantiomeric Ratio (L/D)Murchison Extract173Trace-Strong L-enrichment Murchison Residue519Trace691Strong L-enrichment The detection of threonine primarily in the extract residue suggests that its hydroxyl side chain promotes strong binding to clay minerals within the meteorite matrix. While non-proteinogenic amino acids in meteorites are typically racemic, the observed L-enrichment of threonine in Murchison remains a subject of intense debate. It may reflect terrestrial contamination, but some researchers propose it could be indigenous, potentially resulting from stereoselective mineral catalysis or the influence of circularly polarized light during the aqueous alteration phase on the parent asteroid.Asteroid Sample Return: Ryugu and BennuThe JAXA Hayabusa2 and NASA OSIRIS-REx missions have provided pristine samples from asteroids Ryugu and Bennu, respectively. These samples are crucial for eliminating the variable of terrestrial contamination. Preliminary studies using three-dimensional high-performance liquid chromatography (3D-HPLC) successfully quantified several proteinogenic amino acids, including serine, alanine, and aspartic acid, in Ryugu. Although threonine was not a primary target in the initial 3D-HPLC reports, its ubiquity in related CM-type chondrites suggest it is likely present, formed via the hydrothermal processing of formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and ammonia during the melting of parent body ice.Mineral Catalysis and Geochemical EnvironmentsMinerals were the first \"enzymes\" of the prebiotic world. Their surfaces provided the necessary platform for the concentration of reactants and the lowering of activation energy barriers for complex syntheses like that of threonine.Transition Metal Sulfides: The Iron-Sulfur WorldTransition metal sulfide minerals, such as greigite ($Fe_{3}S_{4}$), pyrite ($FeS_{2}$), and nickel-bearing sulfides, are central to the \"metabolism-first\" hypothesis. In alkaline hydrothermal vent environments, these minerals are thought to catalyze the fixation of $CO$ and $CO_{2}$ via pathways that prefigure the biological Wood-Ljungdahl pathway. Nickel isotopes found in early Earth rocks suggest that nickel may have played a more profound role than previously recognized in catalyzing the polymerization of amino acids and the fixation of carbon. Recent evidence also highlights that single amino acids, such as cysteine or histidine, can coordinate with metal ions to form catalytically active assemblies that accelerate reactions under the extreme conditions of hydrothermal vents.Clay Minerals: Montmorillonite and Concentration MechanismsMontmorillonite, a clay mineral derived from the weathering of volcanic ash, is well-known for its catalytic role in RNA oligomerization. However, its relevance to threonine synthesis lies in its adsorption properties. Clays can selectively concentrate organic molecules from the \"dilute\" prebiotic ocean, facilitating the high-density environments required for multi-body reactions like the Strecker synthesis or aldol condensations. The interlayer spacing of montmorillonite expands upon contact with water, creating a shielded microenvironment where fragile intermediates, such as the threonine precursor nitriles, can be protected from hydrolytic degradation.Environmental Drivers: Vents, Ice, and Tidal FlatsThe environmental context dictates the specific chemical potential available for synthesis.Hydrothermal Vents: These systems provide steady gradients of temperature, pH, and redox potential. Simulation experiments demonstrate that hydrothermal synthesis from $HCN$ and $H_{2}S$ can produce glycine, alanine, and serine, but threonine synthesis is often limited by the thermal instability of the molecule at temperatures exceeding $150^\\circ C$.Frozen Solutions: Freezing a reaction mixture concentrates solutes into brine pockets. Research into non-enzymatic aldol condensation has shown that complex sugars and potentially amino acids like threonine can be synthesized in ice at $-20^\\circ C$. The low temperature also serves a protective function, preventing the rapid decarboxylation that threonine undergoes at higher temperatures.Tidal Flats and Volcanic Hot Springs: These subaerial environments allow for wet-dry cycles, which are critical for the concentration of solutes and the driving of condensation reactions. Ultraviolet light in these shallow pools acts as a key energy source for the photoredox chemistry required in the cyanosulfidic pathway.Kinetic Stability and DegradationThe prebiotic relevance of threonine is constrained by its stability. Understanding how long threonine persists in the environment is essential for determining whether detected molecules are relicts of early Earth processes or the products of ongoing synthesis.Decarboxylation and Half-LivesThreonine is relatively unstable toward hydrothermal decarboxylation compared to simpler amino acids like glycine or alanine. Kinetic studies using FT-IR spectroscopy have provided the following insights into its degradation:Temperature Dependence: The rate of threonine transformation into glycine and other products increases significantly above $120^\\circ C$.pH Stability: Threonine is more thermally stable in alkaline solutions, which supports its survival in alkaline hydrothermal vent environments or the interior oceans of icy moons like Enceladus.The One-Billion Year Rule: At a temperature of 273 K (the freezing point of water), threonine is estimated to have a maximum persistence of 1 billion years. If detected in hydrothermally active ocean worlds at concentrations above 1 nM, it must have been synthesized recently.Temperature (K)EnvironmentEstimated Stability/Half-lifePrimary Degradation Product273Freezing Point$< 1$ Billion Years- 29825 \u00b0CDays (for associated RNA)- 394-433HydrothermalHours to DaysGlycine 573+Black SmokerMinutes$CO_{2}$, $NH_{3}$, Hydrocarbons These kinetic constraints suggest that for threonine to have played a role in the origin of life, its synthesis must have been either continuous or occurred in cooler, protected environments such as clay-rich sediment or ice-brine systems.Unresolved Challenges and Future Research DirectionsDespite the identification of several plausible pathways, threonine remains one of the more elusive proteinogenic amino acids in prebiotic chemistry due to several \"bottlenecks.\"The Stereochemical ChallengeThe primary challenge remains diastereoselectivity and enantioselectivity. While biology utilizes only L-threonine, prebiotic syntheses like the Strecker reaction or simple aldol condensation typically yield racemic mixtures of both threonine and its diastereomer, allothreonine. While specific catalysts like chiral pyridoxal mimics or rigid mineral surfaces show promise in inducing stereoselectivity, the transition from these laboratory-scale successes to a global geochemical phenomenon is not yet fully understood.The Dilution and Concentration ProblemThe synthesis of a four-carbon amino acid like threonine requires the collision of multiple precursors ($C_{1}, C_{2}, N, S$ sources). In the vast prebiotic ocean, the probability of such an event is extremely low. Most successful models rely on mechanisms of concentration, such as evaporation in lagoons or adsorption onto minerals like montmorillonite. However, reconciling these localized \"hotspots\" with the widespread emergence of life remains a fundamental question in origins-of-life research.Transition to MetabolismAnother significant gap is the understanding of how abiotically synthesized threonine was integrated into the first metabolic networks. Threonine\u2019s modern biosynthesis from aspartate is a complex, multi-step process involving multiple kinases and dehydrogenases. How a primitive \"protometabolism\" bridged the gap between spontaneous threonine synthesis and the regulated enzymatic production seen in the Last Universal Common Ancestor (LUCA) is still being elucidated through studies of non-enzymatic metabolic cycles.In summary, the prebiotic synthesis of threonine is no longer viewed as a random event in a \"primordial soup.\" Instead, it is understood as a product of sophisticated, systems-level chemistry involving cyanide, sulfur, and UV light, facilitated by mineral catalysis and environmental gradients. The detection of threonine in extraterrestrial materials confirms that these pathways are active across the solar system, reinforcing the notion that the building blocks of life are a natural outcome of planetary and geochemical evolution. Future research will likely continue to integrate high-resolution analytical data from asteroid return missions with complex computational models to further resolve the stereochemical and concentration challenges that currently persist.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_