ogous to meteoritic chemistry. While the concept is interesting and aligns with literature on Murchison meteorite amino acids, the 8-step length introduces cumulative yield losses. The acetaldehyde + glycolaldehyde cross-aldol step remains the weakest link. The pathway provides important contextual support for extraterrestrial formation but is less efficient than terrestrial alternatives.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"Consider adding aqueous alteration conditions specific to parent body environments\",\n                \"Provide yield estimates for cumulative 8-step pathway\"\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_005\": 0.68,\n                \"rxn_006\": 0.91,\n                \"rxn_007\": 0.88,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.82,\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.78,\n                \"rxn_015\": 0.82,\n                \"rxn_017\": 0.80\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.82,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.90,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.82,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.82,\n            \"feedback\": \"Excellent pathway that combines the cyanosulfidic entry (generating C2, C3 building blocks) with the prebiotic sugar pathway exit (thioester formation). This bridges both major literature frameworks into a single coherent route. The cyanosulfidic generation of glyceraldehyde feeds directly into erythrose formation, and the thioester activation provides a prebiotically relevant activated amino acid. The rxn_005 HCN generation concern persists.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\n                \"Strengthen the HCN formation step with a more established mechanism\"\n