tes provide the precursors: CO2 reduction gives formate then formaldehyde, while FTT gives acetaldehyde. These converge in surface cross-aldol to lactaldehyde, then Strecker and hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_002", "rxn_004", "rxn_012", "rxn_014", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_014", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Mixed FTT + Formose \u2192 Glyceraldehyde \u2192 Erythrose \u2192 Thioester \u2192 Threonine", "description": "FTT formaldehyde undergoes formose self-condensation to glycolaldehyde, then aldol with formaldehyde to glyceraldehyde, then chain extension with formaldehyde to erythrose. Erythrose enters the thioester pathway. Demonstrates deep hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical connectivity.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_015", "rxn_017"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_015", "mol_017"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_009", "mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_003", "mol_014"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_009", "description": "Formaldehyde \u2014 the primary C1 building block, produced by two hydrothermal routes and consumed in four surface reactions", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "Glycolaldehyde \u2014 the key C2 sugar, produced by cyanosulfidic hydrolysis and formose condensation, feeds aldol and sugar pathways", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_007", "rxn_008"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_009", "rxn_010"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "Lactaldehyde \u2014 the direct Strecker precursor for threonine, produced by cross-aldol and photoreduction, converges two major routes before aminonitrile formation", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_014"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_013", "description": "Glyceraldehyde \u20